  <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00008"
     xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
     Layout:TextAlign="Center"
     rolemaps-to="P"
    >
   <?MarkedContent page="1" ?> MJD
  </text>
  <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00009"
     xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
     Layout:TextAlign="Center"
     rolemaps-to="P"
    >
   <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>May 20, 2016
  </text>
 </text-unit>
 <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
    id="ID.00010"
    rolemaps-to="Part"
   >
  <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00011"
     xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
     Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
     rolemaps-to="P"
    >
   <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>The following examples are derived from 
   <Em xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
      id="ID.00012"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>Homology manifold bordism
   </Em>
   <?MarkedContent page="1" ?> by Heather Johnston and Andrew Ranicki (Trans. Amer. Math. Soc. 352 no 11 (2000), PII: S 0002-9947(00)02630-1).
  </text>
 </text-unit>
 <Sect xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
    id="ID.00013"
   >
  <section xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00014"
     rolemaps-to="H1"
    >
   <section-number xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00015"
      rolemaps-to="Span"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>4 
   </section-number>
   <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>Homology manifold bordism
  </section>
  <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00016"
     rolemaps-to="Part"
    >
   <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00017"
      xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
      Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
      rolemaps-to="P"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>The results of Johnston [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00018"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?Jo
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>] on homology manifolds are extended here. It is not possible to investigate transversality by geometric methods—as in [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00019"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?Jo
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>] we employ bordism and surgery instead.
   </text>
  </text-unit>
  <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00020"
     rolemaps-to="Part"
    >
   <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00021"
      xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
      Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
      rolemaps-to="P"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>The proof of transversality is indirect, relying heavily on surgery theory—see Kirby and Siebenmann [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00022"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?KS
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>, III, §1], Marin [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00023"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?M
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>] and Quinn [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00024"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?Q3
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>]. We shall use the formulation in terms of topological block bundles of Rourke and Sanderson [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00025"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?RS
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>].
   </text>
  </text-unit>
  <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00026"
     rolemaps-to="Part"
    >
   <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00027"
      xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
      Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
      rolemaps-to="P"
     >
    <Formula xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00028"
       title="math"
       af="tag-AFfile1.tex"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:Placement="Inline"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>Q
    </Formula>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?> is a codimension 
    <Formula xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00029"
       title="math"
       af="tag-AFfile2.tex"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:Placement="Inline"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>q
    </Formula>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?> subspace by Theorem 4.9 of Rourke and Sanderson [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00030"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?RS
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>]. (Hughes, Taylor and Williams [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00031"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?HTW
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>] obtained a topological regular neigh­borhood theorem for arbitrary submanifolds ….)
   </text>
  </text-unit>
  <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00032"
     rolemaps-to="Part"
    >
   <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00033"
      xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
      Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
      rolemaps-to="P"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>Wall [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00034"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?Wa
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>, Chapter 11] obtained a codimension 
    <Formula xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00035"
       title="math"
       af="tag-AFfile3.tex"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:Placement="Inline"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>q
    </Formula>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?> splitting obstruction ….
   </text>
  </text-unit>
  <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00036"
     rolemaps-to="Part"
    >
   <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00037"
      xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
      Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
      rolemaps-to="P"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>… following the work of Cohen [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00038"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?Co
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>] on 
    <Formula xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00039"
       title="math"
       af="tag-AFfile4.tex"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:Placement="Inline"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>PL
    </Formula>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?> manifold transversality.
   </text>
  </text-unit>
  <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00040"
     rolemaps-to="Part"
    >
   <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00041"
      xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
      Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
      rolemaps-to="P"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>In this case each inverse image is automatically a 
    <Formula xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00042"
       title="math"
       af="tag-AFfile5.tex"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:Placement="Inline"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>PL
    </Formula>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?> submanifold of codi­mension 
    <Formula xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00043"
       title="math"
       af="tag-AFfile6.tex"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:Placement="Inline"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>σ
    </Formula>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?> (Cohen [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00044"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?Co
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>]), so there is no need to use 
    <Formula xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00045"
       title="math"
       af="tag-AFfile7.tex"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:Placement="Inline"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>s
    </Formula>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>-cobordisms.
   </text>
  </text-unit>
  <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00046"
     rolemaps-to="Part"
    >
   <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00047"
      xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
      Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
      rolemaps-to="P"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>Quinn [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00048"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?Q2
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>, 1.1] proved that …
   </text>
  </text-unit>
  <theorem-like xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00049"
     rolemaps-to="Sect"
    >
   <Caption xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
      id="ID.00050"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>Theorem 
    <Lbl xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00051"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>4.1
    </Lbl>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?> (The additive structure of homology manifold bordism, Johnston [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00052"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?Jo
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>])
   </Caption>
   <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00053"
      rolemaps-to="Part"
     >
    <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
       id="ID.00054"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
       rolemaps-to="P"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?> …
    </text>
   </text-unit>
  </theorem-like>
  <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00055"
     rolemaps-to="Part"
    >
   <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00056"
      xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
      Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
      rolemaps-to="P"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>For 
    <Formula xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00057"
       title="math"
       af="tag-AFfile8.tex"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:Placement="Inline"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>m≥5
    </Formula>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?> the Novikov-Wall surgery theory for topological manifolds gives an exact sequence (Wall [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00058"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?Wa
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>, Chapter 10].
   </text>
  </text-unit>
  <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00059"
     rolemaps-to="Part"
    >
   <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00060"
      xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
      Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
      rolemaps-to="P"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>The surgery theory of topological manifolds was extended to homology man­ifolds in Quinn [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00061"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?Q1
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>, 
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00062"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?Q2
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>] and Bryant, Ferry, Mio and Weinberger [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00063"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?BFMW
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>].
   </text>
  </text-unit>
  <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00064"
     rolemaps-to="Part"
    >
   <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00065"
      xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
      Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
      rolemaps-to="P"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>The 4-periodic obstruction is equivalent to an 
    <Formula xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00066"
       title="math"
       af="tag-AFfile9.tex"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:Placement="Inline"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>m
    </Formula>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>-dimensional homology man­ifold, by [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00067"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?BFMW
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>].
   </text>
  </text-unit>
  <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00068"
     rolemaps-to="Part"
    >
   <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00069"
      xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
      Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
      rolemaps-to="P"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>Thus, the surgery exact sequence of [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00070"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?BFMW
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>] does not follow Wall [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00071"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?Wa
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>] in relating homology manifold structures and normal invariants.
   </text>
  </text-unit>
  <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00072"
     rolemaps-to="Part"
    >
   <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00073"
      xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
      Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
      rolemaps-to="P"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>… the canonical 
    <Formula xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00074"
       title="math"
       af="tag-AFfile10.tex"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:Placement="Inline"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>TOP
    </Formula>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?> reduction ([
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00075"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>?FP
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>]) of the Spivak normal fibration of 
    <Formula xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00076"
       title="math"
       af="tag-AFfile11.tex"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:Placement="Inline"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>M
    </Formula>
    <?MarkedContent page="1" ?>…
   </text>
  </text-unit>
  <theorem-like xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00077"
     rolemaps-to="Sect"
    >
   <Caption xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
      id="ID.00078"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="2" ?>Theorem 
    <Lbl xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00079"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="2" ?>4.2
    </Lbl>
    <?MarkedContent page="2" ?> (Johnston [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00080"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="2" ?>?Jo
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="2" ?>])
   </Caption>
   <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00081"
      rolemaps-to="Part"
     >
    <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
       id="ID.00082"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
       rolemaps-to="P"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="2" ?> …
    </text>
   </text-unit>
  </theorem-like>
  <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00083"
     rolemaps-to="Part"
    >
   <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00084"
      xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
      Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
      rolemaps-to="P"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="2" ?>Actually [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00085"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="2" ?>?Jo
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="2" ?>, (5.2)] is for 
    <Formula xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00086"
       title="math"
       af="tag-AFfile12.tex"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:Placement="Inline"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="2" ?>m≥7
    </Formula>
    <?MarkedContent page="2" ?>, but we can improve to 
    <Formula xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00087"
       title="math"
       af="tag-AFfile13.tex"
       xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
       Layout:Placement="Inline"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="2" ?>m≥6
    </Formula>
    <?MarkedContent page="2" ?> by a slight variation of the proof as described below.
   </text>
  </text-unit>
  <text-unit xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
     id="ID.00088"
     rolemaps-to="Part"
    >
   <text xmlns="https://www.latex-project.org/ns/dflt"
      id="ID.00089"
      xmlns:Layout="http://iso.org/pdf/ssn/Layout"
      Layout:TextAlign="Justify"
      rolemaps-to="P"
     >
    <?MarkedContent page="2" ?>(This type of surgery on a Poincaré space is in the tradition of Lowell Jones [
    <Link xmlns="http://iso.org/pdf2/ssn"
       id="ID.00090"
      >
     <?MarkedContent page="2" ?>?Jn
     <?ReferencedObject type="Annot" page="1" ?>
    </Link>
    <?MarkedContent page="2" ?>].)
   </text>
  </text-unit>
 </Sect>
</Document>
